<div class="newblue-pro-quote-box"><a name="answer-id-007843"></a>
<div class="newblue-editortext" style="text-align:left">Ethan Russo, MD, Senior Medical Advisor at the Cannabinoid Research Institute, et al., wrote the following in the Jan. 2002 paper titled "Chronic Cannabis Use in the Compassionate Investigational New Drug Program: An Examination of Benefits and Adverse Effects of Legal Clinical Cannabis," published in the <I>Journal of Cannabis Therapeutics</i>:</div><br />
<div class="newblue-quote-indent">
<div class="newblue-editortext" style="text-align:left">"Cannabis smoking, even of a crude, low-grade product, provides effective symptomatic relief of pain, muscle spasms, and intraocular pressure elevations in selected patients failing other modes of treatment...<br />
<br />
It is the authors' opinion that the Compassionate IND program should be reopened and extended to other patients in need of clinical cannabis. Failing that, local, state and federal laws might be amended to provide regulated and monitored clinical cannabis to suitable candidates."</div><br />
<span>
Jan. 2002 - <a href="/view.source.php?sourceID=000275" alt="Ethan Russo, MD" title="Ethan Russo, MD" target="_blank">Ethan Russo, MD&nbsp;<i class="fas fa-star pcstar"></i><i class="fas fa-star pcstar"></i><i class="fas fa-star pcstar"></i><i class="fas fa-star pcstar"></i></a><br />
