<div class="newblue-con-quote-box"><a name="answer-id-007795"></a>
<div class="newblue-editortext" style="text-align:left">Nicholas A. Pace, MD, Clinical Associate Professor of Medicine at New York University Medical Center, wrote the following in an Apr. 26, 2006 "Letter to the Editor," published in the <i>New York Times</i>:</div><br />
<div class="newblue-quote-indent">
<div class="newblue-editortext" style="text-align:left">"Recent research shows that marijuana has detrimental effects on the brain, lungs, heart and fertility. The THC (the main ingredient in marijuana) content in marijuana used today is twice as strong as 30 years ago.<br />
<br />
The false impression that there is a medical need for marijuana confuses and misleads a poorly informed compassionate public in believing that the medical profession is withholding helpful medication from the sick."</div><br />
<span>
Apr. 26, 2006 - <a href="/view.source.php?sourceID=001559" alt="Nicholas A. Pace, MD" title="Nicholas A. Pace, MD" target="_blank">Nicholas A. Pace, MD&nbsp;<i class="fas fa-star pcstar"></i><i class="fas fa-star pcstar"></i><i class="fas fa-star pcstar"></i><i class="fas fa-star pcstar"></i></a><br />
</span>
</div>
